        {
          "anchor" : "Analog-and-Digital-Signals",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Analog and Digital Signals",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Digital signals only have discrete HIGH and LOW states, which are usually Vcc and 0V. See",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "doc:\/\/Notes\/documentation\/Notes\/Electronic-Systems#Different-Types-of-Signal",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " for more details.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Data is converted from digital to analog using a DAC (digital-analog converter), and from analog to digital",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "using an ADC (guess what that stands for).",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Pull-UpDown-Resistors",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Pull Up\/Down Resistors",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "If you keep a pin “floating”, aka unconnected, what value do you think it is? Most think its just LOW, but in",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "reality its undefined and can be either HIGH or LOW. That means when we have inputs via things like switches",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "or buttons, we need to use pull-up or pull-down circuits to ensure that when the switch or button is open, there",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "is still a well-defined signal.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "identifier" : "Diagram_Pull Up",
              "type" : "image"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "In a pull up circuit, the resistor is connected to Vcc, and the switch is connected to ground. When the switch is",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "closed, the input is LOW, and when the switch is open, the input is HIGH.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "identifier" : "Diagram_Pull Down",
              "type" : "image"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "In a pull down circuit, the resistor is connected to ground, and the switch is connected to Vcc. When the switch is",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "closed, the input is HIGH, and when the switch is open, the input is LOW.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Note that R must be very high, such as 10kΩ, to ensure that the input is not shorted to ground or Vcc when the",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "switch is closed.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The resistor and switch are ALWAYS opposite each other, never on the same side.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Numeric-Representation",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Numeric Representation",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "See ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "doc:\/\/Notes\/documentation\/Notes\/Data-Representation",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " for an introduction to number systems.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "In electronics, we use binary to represent logic. However, there is a special system called BCD (binary coded decimal)",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "that we use to represent numbers in decimal form. In BCD, each digit is represented by a 4-bit binary number.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "header" : "row",
          "rows" : [
